WEBVTT

00:22.120 --> 00:24.920
CHAPTER XXIII

00:27.060 --> 00:33.680
It was eight o'clock when we landed. We walked for a short time on the shore, enjoying the

00:33.680 --> 00:39.980
transitory light, and then retired to the inn and contemplated the lovely scene of waters,

00:40.600 --> 00:46.060
woods and mountains, obscured in darkness yet still displaying their black outlines.

00:49.160 --> 00:54.800
The wind, which had followed in the south, now rose with great violence in the west.

00:55.290 --> 01:01.800
The moon had reached her summit in the heavens and was beginning to descend. The clouds swept

01:01.800 --> 01:08.240
across it swifter than the flight of the vulture and dimmed her rays, while the lake reflected

01:08.240 --> 01:14.820
the scene of the busy heavens, rendered still busier by the restless waves that were beginning

01:14.820 --> 01:23.680
to rise. Suddenly a heavy storm of rain descended. I had been calm during the day,

01:23.680 --> 01:30.960
but so soon as night obscured the shapes of objects, a thousand fears rose in my mind.

01:31.420 --> 01:38.380
I was anxious and watchful, while my right hand grasped the pistol which was hidden in my bosom.

01:39.420 --> 01:47.480
Every sound terrified me, but I resolved that I would sell my life dearly and not shrink from

01:47.480 --> 01:52.640
the conflict until my own life or that of my adversary was extinguished.

01:54.980 --> 02:00.380
Elizabeth observed my agitation for some time in timid and fearful silence,

02:00.820 --> 02:06.140
but there was something in my glance which communicated terror to her and trembling,

02:06.420 --> 02:11.880
she asked. What is it that agitates you, my dear Victor? What is it you fear?

02:13.120 --> 02:19.340
Oh, peace, peace, my love, I replied. This night and all will be safe,

02:19.340 --> 02:28.120
but this night is dreadful, very dreadful. I passed an hour in this state of mind when

02:28.120 --> 02:34.220
suddenly I reflected how fearful the combat which I momentarily expected would be to my wife,

02:35.640 --> 02:40.740
and earnestly I entreated her to retire, resolving not to join her until I had

02:40.740 --> 02:43.840
obtained some knowledge as to the situation of my enemy.

02:45.660 --> 02:51.740
She left me, and I continued some time walking up and down the passages of the

02:51.740 --> 02:57.340
house and inspecting every corner that might afford a retreat to my adversary,

02:58.460 --> 03:04.180
but I discovered no trace of him and was beginning to conjecture that some fortunate

03:04.180 --> 03:11.010
chance had intervened to prevent the execution of his menaces, when suddenly I heard a shrill and

03:11.010 --> 03:17.790
fearful scream. It came from the room into which Elizabeth had retired. As I heard it,

03:17.810 --> 03:22.930
the whole truth rushed into my mind, my arms dropped, the motion of every muscle and fiber

03:22.930 --> 03:28.830
was suspended. I could feel the blood trickling in my veins and tingling in the extremities of

03:28.830 --> 03:36.430
my limbs. The state lasted but for an instant. The scream was repeated, and I rushed into the room.

03:37.870 --> 03:44.990
Great God, why did I not then expire? Why am I here to relate the destruction of the best hope

03:44.990 --> 03:50.830
and the purest creatures of earth? She was there, lifeless and inanimate, thrown across the bed,

03:50.970 --> 03:55.790
her head hanging down and her pale and distorted features half covered by her hair.

03:58.710 --> 04:04.690
Everywhere I turn I see the same figure, her bloodless arms in relaxed form, flung by the

04:04.690 --> 04:15.250
murderer on its bridled rear. Could I behold this and live? Alas, life is obstinate and clings

04:15.250 --> 04:23.670
closest where it is most hated. For a moment only did I lose recollection. I fell senseless on the

04:23.670 --> 04:31.050
ground. When I recovered I found myself surrounded by the people of the inn, their countenance

04:31.050 --> 04:38.570
expressed a breathless terror. But the horror of others appeared only as a mockery, a shadow

04:38.570 --> 04:47.050
of the feelings that oppressed me. I escaped from them to the room where lay the body of Elizabeth,

04:47.190 --> 04:55.590
my love, my wife, so lately living, so dear, so worthy. She had been moved from the posture in

04:55.590 --> 05:01.950
which I had first beheld her, and now as she lay, her head upon her arms and a handkerchief

05:01.950 --> 05:10.070
thrown across her face and neck, I might have supposed her asleep. I rushed towards her and

05:10.070 --> 05:16.770
embraced her with ardor, but the deadly languor and coldness of the limbs told me that what I

05:16.770 --> 05:23.350
now held in my arms had ceased to be the Elizabeth whom I had loved and cherished. Their murderous

05:23.350 --> 05:29.970
mark of the fiend's grasp was on her neck, and the breath had ceased to issue from her lips.

05:33.650 --> 05:40.170
While I still hung over her in the agony of despair, I happened to look up. The windows

05:40.170 --> 05:46.110
of the room had before been darkened, and I felt a kind of panic on seeing the pale yellow light

05:46.110 --> 05:53.330
of the moon illuminate the chamber. The shutters had been thrown back, and with a sensation of

05:53.330 --> 05:59.730
horror not to be described, I saw at the open window a figure the most hideous and abhorred.

06:00.530 --> 06:06.070
A grin was on the face of the monster. He seemed to jeer as with his fiendish finger

06:06.070 --> 06:12.270
he pointed towards the corpse of my wife. I rushed towards the window and, drawing pistol

06:12.270 --> 06:19.170
from my bosom, fired, but he eluded me, leapt from his station and running with the swiftness of

06:19.170 --> 06:27.850
plunged into the lake. The report of the pistol brought a crowd into the room. I pointed to the

06:27.850 --> 06:34.490
spot where he had disappeared, and we followed the track with boats. Nets were cast but in vain.

06:35.950 --> 06:43.110
After passing several hours, we returned. Hopeless, most of my companions believing

06:43.110 --> 06:50.330
it to have been a form conjured up by my fancy. After having landed, they proceeded to search

06:50.330 --> 06:57.930
the country, parties going in different directions among the woods and vines. I attempted to accompany

06:57.930 --> 07:04.550
them and proceed the short distance from the house, but my head whirled round. My steps were

07:04.550 --> 07:11.830
like those of a drunken man, and I felt at last in a state of utter exhaustion. A film covered my

07:11.830 --> 07:19.050
eyes and my skin was parched with the heat of fever. In this state, I was carried back and placed

07:19.050 --> 07:25.790
on a bed, hardly conscious of what had happened. My eyes wandered round the room as if to seek

07:25.790 --> 07:33.170
something that I had lost. After an interval, I rose and, as if by instinct, crawled into the

07:33.860 --> 07:44.550
my beloved lay. There were women weeping around. I hung over it and joined my sad tears to theirs.

07:46.350 --> 07:52.310
All this time, no distinct idea presented itself to my mind, but my thoughts rambled to their

07:52.310 --> 08:02.030
various subjects, reflecting confusedly on my misfortunes and their cause. I was bewildered

08:02.030 --> 08:09.030
in a cloud of wonder and horror. The death of William, the execution of Justine, the murder

08:09.030 --> 08:16.770
of Clairvaux, and lastly of my wife. Even at that moment, I knew not that my only remaining friends

08:16.770 --> 08:24.410
were safe from the malignity of the fiend. My father, even now, might be writhing under his

08:24.410 --> 08:31.630
grasp, and Ernest might be dead at his feet. This idea made me shudder and recalled me to

08:31.630 --> 08:37.590
action. I started up and resolved to return to Geneva with all possible speed.

08:42.390 --> 08:51.390
There were no horses to be procured, and I must return by the lake, but the wind was unfavorable

08:51.390 --> 08:58.510
and the rain fell in torrents. However, it was hardly morning, and I might reasonably hope to

08:58.510 --> 09:06.490
arrive by night. I hired men to row and took my oar myself, where I had always experienced relief

09:06.490 --> 09:15.670
from mental torment and bodily exercise. But the overflowing misery I now felt and the excess of

09:15.670 --> 09:24.230
agitation that I endured rendered me incapable of any exertion. I threw down the oar, and leaning

09:24.230 --> 09:32.930
my head upon my hands gave way to every gloomy idea that arose. If I looked up, I saw scenes

09:32.930 --> 09:38.990
which were familiar to me in my happier time, and which I had contemplated but the day before in

09:38.990 --> 09:47.590
the company of her who was now but a shadow and a recollection. Tears streamed from my eyes. The

09:47.590 --> 09:52.870
rain had ceased for a moment, and I saw the fish play in the waters as they had done a few hours

09:52.870 --> 10:04.930
before. They had then been observed by Elizabeth. Nothing is so painful to the human mind as a great

10:04.930 --> 10:12.190
and sudden change. The sun might shine or the crowds might lure, but nothing could appear to

10:12.190 --> 10:18.970
me as it had done the day before. A fiend had snatched from me every hope of future happiness.

10:19.890 --> 10:26.190
No creature had ever been so miserable as I was. So frightful an event is single in the history of

10:26.190 --> 10:34.030
man. But why should I dwell upon the incidents that followed this last overwhelming event?

10:35.210 --> 10:42.980
Mine has been a tale of horrors. I have reached their acme, and what I must now relate can be

10:43.740 --> 10:55.980
tedious to you. Know that one by one my friends were snatched away. I was left desolate. My own

10:55.980 --> 11:01.620
strength is exhausted, and I must tell in a few words what remains of my hideous narration.

11:05.060 --> 11:12.620
I arrived at Geneva. My father and Ernest yet lived, but the former sunk under the tidings

11:12.620 --> 11:19.900
I bore. I see him now, excellent and venerable old man, his eyes wandered in vacancy, for they

11:19.900 --> 11:25.740
had lost their charm and their delight. He is Elizabeth, his more than daughter, whom he

11:25.740 --> 11:31.740
doted on with all that affection which a man feels, who in the decline of life, having few

11:31.740 --> 11:39.900
affections, clings more earnestly to those that remain. Cursed be the fiend that brought

11:39.900 --> 11:46.960
misery on his grey hairs and doomed him to waste and wretchedness. He could not live under the

11:46.960 --> 11:54.520
horrors that were accumulated around him. The springs of existence suddenly gave way. He was

11:54.520 --> 12:04.320
unable to rise from his bed, and in a few days he died in my arms. What then became of me? I

12:04.320 --> 12:10.360
know not. I lost sensation, and chains and darkness were the only objects that pressed

12:10.360 --> 12:17.420
upon me. Sometimes, indeed, I dreamt that I wandered in flowery meadows and pleasant

12:17.420 --> 12:25.380
bales with the friends of my youth, but I awoke and found myself in a dungeon. Melancholy followed,

12:25.460 --> 12:30.900
but by degrees I gained a clear conception of my miseries and situation, and was then

12:30.900 --> 12:36.780
released from my prison, for they had called me mad, and during many months, as I understood,

12:37.120 --> 12:48.120
a solitary cell had been my habitation. Liberty, however, had been a useless gift to me, had I

12:48.120 --> 12:56.040
not, as I awakened to reason, at the same time awakened to revenge. As the memory of my past

12:56.580 --> 13:02.980
pressed upon me, I began to reflect on their cause, the monster whom I had created, the

13:02.980 --> 13:11.980
miserable demon whom I had sent abroad into the world for my destruction. I was possessed

13:11.980 --> 13:17.560
by a maddening rage when I thought of him, and desired and ardently prayed that I might

13:17.560 --> 13:25.080
have him within my grasp to wreak a great and single revenge on his cursed head.

13:28.080 --> 13:35.120
Nor did my hate long confine itself to useless wishes. I began to reflect on the best means

13:35.120 --> 13:42.100
of securing him, and for this purpose, about a month after my release, I repaired to a criminal

13:42.840 --> 13:50.420
and told him that I had an accusation to make, that I knew the destroyer of my family, and that

13:50.420 --> 13:54.720
I required him to exert his whole authority for the apprehension of the murderer.

13:56.640 --> 14:04.300
The magistrate listened to me with attention and kindness. Be assured, sir, he said. No pains or

14:04.300 --> 14:07.020
exertion on my part shall be spared to discover the villain.

14:08.300 --> 14:17.380
Thank you, I replied. Listen therefore to the deposition that I have to make. It is indeed a

14:17.380 --> 14:23.010
tale so strange that I should fear you would not credit it were it not something in truth which,

14:24.440 --> 14:32.680
however wonderful, forces conviction. The story is too connected to be mistaken for a dream,

14:33.240 --> 14:40.840
and I have no motive for falsehood. My manner, as I thus addressed him,

14:41.000 --> 14:48.780
was impressive but calm. I had formed in my own heart a resolution to pursue my destroyer to death,

14:49.500 --> 14:55.860
and this purpose quieted my agony, and for an interval reconciled me to life.

14:55.860 --> 15:03.260
I now relate my history briefly but with firmness and precision, marking the dates

15:03.260 --> 15:09.160
with accuracy and never deviating into invective or exclamation.

15:11.620 --> 15:14.720
The magistrate appeared at first perfectly incredulous,

15:14.840 --> 15:18.360
but as I continued he became more attentive and interested.

15:21.640 --> 15:26.900
I saw him sometimes shudder with horror, and others a lively surprise,

15:27.300 --> 15:30.820
unmingled with disbelief, was painted on his countenance.

15:32.260 --> 15:37.320
When I had concluded my narration, I said, This is the being whom I accuse,

15:37.920 --> 15:42.400
and for whose seizure and punishment I call upon you to exert your whole power.

15:43.020 --> 15:47.920
It is your duty as magistrate, and I believe and hope that your feelings as a man will not

15:47.920 --> 15:51.720
revolt from the execution of those functions on this occasion.

15:54.520 --> 15:59.960
The address caused a considerable change in the physiognomy of my own auditor.

16:01.180 --> 16:07.020
He had heard my story with that half kind of belief that is given to a tale of spirits

16:07.020 --> 16:11.860
and supernatural events, but when he was called upon to act officially in consequence,

16:11.860 --> 16:15.080
the whole tide of his incredulity returned.

16:16.660 --> 16:22.920
He, however, answered mildly, I would willingly afford you every aid in your pursuit,

16:23.560 --> 16:28.740
but the creature of whom you speak appears to have powers which would put all my exertions

16:28.740 --> 16:33.620
to defiance. Who can follow an animal which can traverse the sea of ice,

16:33.880 --> 16:37.460
and inhabit caves and dens where no man would venture to intrude?

16:38.600 --> 16:45.700
Besides, some months have elapsed since the commission of his crimes,

16:46.220 --> 16:51.080
and no one can conjecture to what place he has wandered or what region he may now inhabit.

16:54.620 --> 16:59.620
I do not doubt that he hovers near the spot which I inhabit, and if he has indeed taken

16:59.620 --> 17:06.020
refuge in the Alps he may be hunted like the Chamois and destroyed as a beast of prey,

17:06.660 --> 17:10.080
but I perceive your thoughts. You do not credit my narrative,

17:10.620 --> 17:15.340
and do not intend to pursue my enemy with the punishment which is his desert.

17:16.740 --> 17:21.900
As I spoke, rage sparkled in my eyes. The magistrate was intimidated.

17:22.040 --> 17:25.720
You are mistaken, said he. I will exert myself,

17:26.840 --> 17:31.900
and if it is in my power to seize the monster, be assured that he shall suffer punishment

17:31.900 --> 17:39.100
proportionate to his crimes, but I fear from what you have yourself described to be his properties

17:39.100 --> 17:44.540
that this will prove impracticable, and thus while every proper measure is pursued,

17:44.980 --> 17:52.380
you should make up your mind to disappointment. That cannot be, but all that I can say will be

17:52.380 --> 17:59.100
of little avail. My revenge is of no moment to you, yet while I allow it to be a vice,

17:59.100 --> 18:05.900
I confess that it is the devouring and only passion of my soul. My rage is unspeakable.

18:06.860 --> 18:11.840
When I reflect that the murderer whom I have turned loose upon society still exists,

18:12.520 --> 18:16.800
you refuse my just demand. I have but one resource, and I devote myself,

18:17.560 --> 18:20.460
either in my life or death, to his destruction.

18:23.520 --> 18:29.360
I trembled with excess of agitation as I said this. There was a frenzy in my manner,

18:29.700 --> 18:34.920
and something, I doubt not, of that haughty fierceness which the martyrs of old are said

18:34.920 --> 18:41.220
to have possessed. But to a German magistrate whose mind was occupied by far other ideas

18:41.220 --> 18:46.920
than those of devotion and heroism, this elevation of mine had much the appearance of madness.

18:47.780 --> 18:54.020
He endeavoured to soothe me as a nurse, as a child, and reverted to my tale as the effects

18:54.020 --> 19:02.900
of delirium. Man, I cried, how ignorant art thou in thy pride of wisdom! Cease! You know

19:02.900 --> 19:10.960
not what it is you say. I broke from the house angry and disturbed, and retired to meditate.

19:12.080 --> 19:19.380
I broke from the house angry and disturbed, and retired to meditate on some other mode of action.

